abstract.0: Oracle Cloud Infrastructure provides DevOps practitioners with the services required to automate deployment of large, complex distributed systems while giving engineers the flexibility to choose the languages and tools of their preference. In this session explore DevOps solutions, including expanded support for popular tools and languages. Learn how to solve problems with this suite of offerings, how it’s differentiated from other options on the market, and how the product team made these choices.  DevOps professionals are encouraged to bring their own scenarios to the table to better understand how Oracle Cloud Infrastructure can address their needs and accelerate their agile development projects.
abstract.1: Edge services provide the fundamental building blocks for securing and scaling internet-facing applications deployed on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure. The combination of a domain name system, traffic management, web application firewalls, and internet monitoring route and protect traffic for applications and web services. Customers can build access rules for protection and plan application migrations through global load balancing with granular control and visibility.  These services provide key components to building highly scalable, available, and performant web applications across the global Oracle Cloud Infrastructure footprint. In this session learn more about these services directly from the product manager building the services in a candid discussion format.
abstract.2: In this interactive session learn various options, methods, and best practices to migrate your workloads to Oracle Cloud Infrastructure from your data center, Oracle Cloud Infrastructure Compute Classic, AWS, or other cloud platforms. Dive deep into migration methodology selection based on the source environment, applications to migrate, amount of data, and down time sensitivity. The session also looks into partner tools and services available to make your migration to Oracle Cloud Infrastructure a smooth experience.
abstract.3: In this session hear directly from the team leaders building big data and analytics on Oracle Cloud Infrastructure. Learn about what they built, why they prioritized what they did, and how it has a big business impact. Dig deeper into the three guiding principles for the product: Provide the most performant, reliable, consistent, and cheapest infrastructure platform possible to run advanced analytics workloads at enterprise scale; ensure an open platform that allows customers to easily integrate all the big data ecosystem partners across Hadoop, Spark, data integration, AI, and machine learning technologies (Cloudera, Hortonworks, MapR, H20.ai, etc.); and deliver innovation with the big data services from Oracle’s recent acquisitions.
abstract.4: In this session get a deeper understanding of Oracle Cloud Management tools including tags, compartments, and billing alerts used to implement an effective chargeback system. The session also explores nested compartments and how they can be used to organize Oracle Cloud Infrastructure resources. Get visibility into the products and features as well as insight into the process used to prioritize and define these features.

1.bio:
Charlie Baker is currently the Sr. Director Product Management on the Oracle Cloud Infrastructure team and oversees the roadmap and strategic direction for infrastructure-as-a-service edge services at Oracle.  He has led product management and marketing teams across Internet, telecommunications infrastructure, and monitoring businesses across OEM, direct sales, and SaaS models.  In addition to his career in product management, Charlie served as an officer in the U.S. Air Force and managed programs for the design, upgrade and deployment of space defense and optical telescope systems. 
Charlie is a graduate of the U.S. Air Force Academy and earned his MBA from Boston University.

4.bio: Martin is a Principal Product Manager with the OCI Foundations team.  He leads the Compartment and Tagging teams to deliver great solutions to our end users.  Discovering and deploying solutions to customer’s complex governance needs is what he finds most rewarding.    Prior to Oracle Martin has had a productive career as a Product Manager at Tableau software and also has 20 years of experience in Program Management at Microsoft.   Martin has been awarded six patents including one that covers the methods of synchronizing multiple computing devices and has an additional fourteen patent applications.
